problem link: https://leetcode.com/problems/diameter-of-binary-tree/description/

Intuition
The diameter of a binary tree is the length of the longest path between any two nodes. This path may or may not pass through the root.

For every node, if we know the heights of its left and right subtrees, then the longest path passing through that node is simply:

left_height + right_height

As we recursively compute the height of each subtree, we can simultaneously calculate the diameter passing through every node and maintain the maximum diameter encountered so far.

Since each recursive call returns the height of the current subtree, the parent node can use this information to compute its own height and potential diameter.

Approach
Initialize a variable result to store the maximum diameter found during the traversal.
Create a recursive helper function solve(node) that returns the height of the subtree rooted at node.
If the current node is None, return 0.
Recursively compute the heights of the left and right subtrees.
The longest path passing through the current node is left_height + right_height.
Update result if this path is larger than the current maximum diameter.
Return 1 + max(left_height, right_height) as the height of the current subtree.
After the traversal completes, return result.

Complexity
Time complexity:
Time Complexity: O(N)
Every node is visited exactly once, and all computations performed at each node take constant time.
Space Complexity: O(H)
The recursion stack can grow up to the height of the tree H.
In the worst case (a skewed tree), H = N, so the space complexity is O(N).
For a balanced tree, H = O(log N).
Code
# Definition for a binary tree node.
# class TreeNode:
#     def __init__(self, val=0, left=None, right=None):
#         self.val = val
#         self.left = left
#         self.right = right
class Solution:
    def diameterOfBinaryTree(self, root: Optional[TreeNode]) -> int:
        result = 0
        def solve(node):
            nonlocal result
            if node is None: return 0
            left = solve(node.left)
            right = solve(node.right)
            total = left + right
            result = max(total,result)
            return 1 + max(left,right)
        solve(root)
        return result
